message_content: Happy New Year! How was your New Year's Day morning run? The air here is exceptionally fresh, and I felt invigorated after the run. How is the weather over there?

Mr. Qian, Happy New Year! I have just completed my 2024 personal review, with key achievements and areas for improvement summarized in a report. I would like to schedule a 15-minute meeting with you on the first working day after the holiday to briefly present this and seek your guidance. Would that be convenient for you?

Zheng Wenbo, Happy New Year. I just finished listening to a podcast about the macroeconomic outlook for 2025, which included several interesting perspectives on the restructuring of supply chains in the Asia-Pacific region. I've sent my notes and the link to your email. Feel free to take a look when you have time, and we can discuss it after the holiday.

Sun Xiaoya, Happy New Year. I have compiled some case materials on "loss aversion" in behavioral finance within recent market contexts, which I believe offer valuable insights for our client communications. These materials have been uploaded to the team's shared drive under the "2025 Learning Resources" folder. Please feel free to review them when you have time.
Dad, Mom, and Xiaoran, Happy New Year! Let's have a video call around 9:20 p.m. I'll head home after dinner here and would like to chat with you.
Okay, son, your mom and I will be waiting at home. I'll talk to your sister about it. Drive safely on the road.
Bro, Dad told me, I'll be online at 9:20 sharp! Looking forward to chatting with you and our parents!

Wenbo, I have compiled the key tracking points and market data charts for the AI chip industry for this morning's meeting materials. Please review them and let me know if there are any additions or adjustments needed.

Mr. Huang, regarding the consumer fund you inquired about, I have prepared a brief analysis and recommendations, which have been sent to your email. Please check. Feel free to reach out if you have any questions.

Mr. Lin, regarding the cross-border investment tax issues you inquired about, I have received your email and started researching. I have preliminarily reviewed the relevant tax treaties and foreign exchange regulations, and will provide you with a risk advisory and a list of key points tonight. Detailed recommendations will be provided tomorrow after consulting with the legal advisor.

Dear Mr. Huang, this is Feng Haoran from Huatai Securities. Regarding the service priorities for the new year, we have preliminarily planned global asset allocation and tax optimization strategies. We would like to schedule a video strategy review with you. Could you please let us know which time slot next week would be convenient for you?

【Photography Workshop】You have successfully registered for the "Street Narrative & Complex Lighting Portrait" workshop. Start time: 2025-01-10 19:00. Location: XX Imaging Center. Reply TD to unsubscribe if you have any questions.

Bro, regarding the technology client expansion plan decided in this morning's meeting, I have drafted a preliminary list and contact strategy for the Shenzhen circle and sent it to your email. Please take a look when you have time and provide some feedback.
Mr. Qian, today's work has been wrapped up, all emails have been processed, and tomorrow's to-do list has been updated in the shared document. Wishing you a pleasant weekend!
Mom, I'm driving home from work now. There's some traffic on the road, so I'll probably be home around 6:30. I've ordered takeout for dinner. Have you and Dad eaten yet?

Mom, I've noticed from your recent posts on social media that your cooking skills have been improving. Everything is going well with my work and studies here, though the weather in Changsha is a bit humid. Please take good care of yourselves, both you and Dad.

Mom, I just got home. I had a great time chatting with friends at dinner today. I took some photos by the river in the afternoon and wanted to share them with you—the sunset over the Xiang River was especially beautiful. How are you and Dad doing today?
The photos are really well taken! We're doing fine, your dad is watching TV. Drive safely at night, get some rest early, and don't stay up late.
Mom, I made tomato, egg, and mushroom noodles for lunch, and also fried some luncheon meat. It tasted pretty good. What did you and Dad have for lunch?

Mr. Shen, the tasting session this afternoon was excellent. The flavor profile of the Yunnan beans was truly impressive. Regarding the Baoshan sun-dried beans I just purchased, the recommended pour-over parameters you suggested are a water temperature of 92 degrees and a coffee-to-water ratio of 1:15, right? Let me jot that down.
Dad, Mom, I'm home and just finished unpacking the newly bought coffee beans. Is it convenient to have a video call around 7:30 p.m.? I'd like to chat with you.
Feng Jianguo: Okay, son. Your mother and I have just finished dinner. We'll be waiting for you at 7:30.

Mr. Huang, regarding your inquiry this morning about the fluctuations in technology stocks, I have compiled a detailed analysis and corresponding recommendations into an email, which has been sent to your mailbox. Please check it at your convenience. Should you have any questions, feel free to contact me at any time.

Xiaoya, I have compiled the initial contact list and key communication points for the technology client outreach and sent them to your work email. If convenient, you may review them before the meeting.
The financial section of the analysis report on the AI chip company has been completed and supplemented. The full report has been sent to your email for your review.
Mom, I just finished studying and came out for a walk to relax. The CFA review went fairly well today. You and Dad should rest early and don't wait for me.

Mom, I had breakfast after my morning run. I heard on the financial news that the market has been quite volatile lately. How are you and Dad doing? Remember to take your blood pressure medication on time.
Bro, shall we meet at Old Changsha for lunch? My treat. We can also chat about how your CFA exam preparation is going. I've been studying for it recently too.
Sure, I was actually hoping to learn from you as well. Shall we meet in the lobby downstairs at 12 o'clock?

[Ping An Health] Dear customer, the product information for the "Parent Medical Insurance" you inquired about has been sent via email. Please check your inbox. If you would like to schedule an appointment with an advisor for a detailed explanation, please reply with "1".

Mom, I've finished organizing the information on several health insurance plans for you and Dad to review, with a focus on comparing the health declarations and renewal conditions. I'll explain the details to you during our video call this weekend.

I: Good morning, Mr. Qian. Due to poor road conditions from the rain today, I expect to arrive at the office about 10 minutes late. I will begin handling the client communication and report refinement work for this morning on schedule.

Due to my medical check-up tomorrow morning, the client conference call scheduled for the morning has been coordinated with Zheng Wenbo, who will follow up on my behalf. I have already shared the key points with him.

Bro, I have sent the key discussion points and our bottom-line price for tomorrow's 10 AM conference call with Hongda Capital to your email. I have a medical check-up tomorrow morning, so I'll have to trouble you to host the call. Please feel free to contact me if any issues arise.

Mom, I'm off work now, a bit later than usual today. I have a medical check-up tomorrow morning and need to fast. I'll just order some takeout for dinner tonight. Please take care of yourselves at home, you and Dad. There's been a lot of flu going around recently.

Hello Mr. Shen, this is Feng Haoran. I would like to inquire if you still have the Yunnan Baishan sun-dried coffee beans in stock at your shop. If available, could you please reserve a bag for me? I plan to pick it up around Saturday afternoon. Thank you!

Mr. Qian, the first draft of this week's "Technology and New Energy Sector Weekly Review" report has been completed and uploaded to the shared folder for your review. The main updates include the valuation data for the semiconductor equipment sector and an analysis of the recent policy impacts on the new energy vehicle industry chain.

Wenbo, thank you for the discussion on semiconductor valuation this afternoon. The report has been finalized and submitted to General Manager Qian. The data source you mentioned has been verified and updated. Attached is the final version for your reference.
Mom, I just finished showering and saw the messages in the group chat. I've saved the location of the restaurant for tomorrow's dinner, so don't worry. You should also rest early.
Yunfei, I've prepared some thoughts on ESG investing and recent market fluctuations for our Saturday morning run. I'd like to discuss them with you and hear your insights.
Mr. Shen, can I pick up the Yunnan Baoshan sun-dried coffee beans I reserved today? I plan to arrive at the shop around 5:30 PM.
Certainly, Mr. Feng. The beans are ready, and we have just received a new batch of Panama Geisha today. Would you like to give it a try?
Jun Jie, I will leave the café around 6:30 and should arrive at Kimuraya by 7:00. Does that time work for you?

Mr. Huang, I am currently preparing the materials for this afternoon's video conference. The focus will be on elaborating the ESG investment philosophy and the combination plan of RSUs and performance stock options that you previously expressed interest in. The initial draft is expected to be completed in the morning, and I will send it to you for preview at that time.
Mom, my back has been a bit tight lately, so I switched from morning runs to stretching. How are you and Dad doing? It's gotten colder in Changsha, so please make sure to stay warm.
Bro, how about going to a Hunan restaurant for lunch? We can grab a coffee at St. Jophis afterwards to perk up.

Mom, I'm off work and driving home now. I'd like to have a video call with you and Dad tonight, around 7 o'clock.
Mom, I'm heading out to work. It's getting colder today, so please make sure you and Dad stay warm at home. I'll be back for dinner tonight.

President Qian, Part Two of the equity incentive case study (Tencent vs. Alibaba comparison) has been completed. The key points have been organized into a comparison table and sent to your email. Please check.

Xiao Ran, have you been busy with work lately? I've just finished up on my end, and I'm going to an art exhibition tomorrow. You mentioned last time that you were thinking about changing jobs—how is your resume revision coming along?
Mom, I listened to CFA audio during my morning run today and felt in good form. How have you and Dad been lately? The temperature has dropped in Changsha, so please keep warm.

Mom, I'm off work and heading to the supermarket to buy some groceries. What would you like for dinner? I'll check if there's any fresh chicken breast and broccoli.

Xu Jianing: The photos taken today are so atmospheric! Especially that shot of the cafe window view—the play of light and shadow is absolutely stunning. Have you exported them yet? Send them over for me to take a look.

Mom, it's getting colder today. Please remember to dress warmly when you and Dad go out, so you don't catch a cold. Everything is going well with my work here. I'll contact you again in the evening.

Today has been quite fulfilling; I cooked some Hubei cuisine and planned the Spring Festival gifts. How about you? Are you free to meet up over the weekend?

Dear Mr. Huang,  

I have received your email confirming the video conference scheduled for next Monday at 3:00 PM. I have already added the meeting to my calendar and have begun preparing the materials. Li Wei: The color reproduction is better than I expected. Portability is indeed its greatest advantage, making it suitable for outdoor shooting. However, the heat dissipation is average during sustained high-power output, so for commercial shoots, you might still need to use larger lights.

Haozi, the photography workshop ended today, and I met two new friends. Regarding that industrial vision project you mentioned last time, shall we schedule a detailed discussion after the Spring Festival?
Yunfei, are you available around 3 p.m.? I will bring you the pothos and monstera from my home and explain to you in person how to care for them.

Mom, I'll be back home tomorrow. I've basically finished packing. I've brought some dark tea for Dad, some pastries for you, and some skincare products for Xiaoran. It's getting colder in Wuhan, so please make sure to wear more clothes at home.

Dear colleagues, I have completed all the tasks at hand and updated my holiday status. Wishing everyone an early Happy Chinese New Year! We'll meet again after the holiday.

I: Good afternoon, Mr. Lin. I have added the product details and risk reminders mentioned during the video conference to the appendix of the proposal PDF. The updated file has been sent to your email. Please check it.
Yunfei, let's meet at the East Gate of Yuelu Mountain tomorrow morning, same time as usual at 6:30. I've brought the newly purchased energy gels for you to try.

Additionally, the zodiac stamp market seems to have experienced some fluctuations recently, and I'd like to hear your thoughts on it.
Sun Xiaoya, congratulations on your promotion! See you at the dinner tonight. I've prepared a little surprise for you.
Zheng Wenbo, don't forget about the dinner gathering tonight. We agreed to give Xiaoya a gift together.

Mom, I'm driving to the cafe now. The traffic is a bit heavy, so I'll probably arrive in about half an hour. You and Dad should stay warm at home—it's gotten colder today.

Me: Mom, I just checked the app, and both your and Dad's blood pressure readings for today look good. Are you getting used to the health monitoring device? Remember to rest early.

Good, son. Glad to hear the treatment went smoothly. Come home for dinner tonight; I've made soup for you. Your father's blood pressure is a bit high, so remind him to take his medicine tonight.

Mom, the temperature has dropped today. Please make sure you and Dad stay warm at home and don't catch a cold at night. My work here is almost finished. Tomorrow is my last day at work, and I'll come home to see you both on New Year's Day.
Xuanzi, today was the last session of my shoulder and neck rehabilitation therapy. The doctor said the results are quite good—finally free! Are you available to meet up this weekend?
Congratulations! We must celebrate. I'm free Saturday afternoon. Shall we have a drink at the usual place?
Rain Qing, let's have a video chat tonight. I just finished a meeting and will be home around 20:30. I'll call you then to share my reflections on this year's review and also hear your good news.

Zheng Wenbo, good morning. I need to report to General Manager Qian this morning. In the afternoon, our department will work together on the year-end wrap-up. If there are any documents or data on your side that require my assistance, let's discuss them after lunch.
Okay, no problem. I have several customer inquiry records that need to be archived. I'll come to you after lunch.

Mom, I just finished packing up my camera and am about to make a cup of coffee. I'll video call you in a bit. Work went really smoothly today, and I finished my promotion presentation. I'm in a particularly good mood.
Okay son, your dad and I just finished dinner and were just thinking of you. Don't drink coffee that's too strong—it'll affect your sleep at night. We're waiting for your video call.
Bro, I heard you've completed your promotion presentation? Congratulations! Show me your new lens on video call tonight. I've been thinking about getting a prime lens myself lately.

Yunfei, I have planned a round-trip run of about 8 kilometers starting from the South Gate of Yuelu Mountain on the morning of New Year's Day. Are you available to join me tomorrow? It's cold, so it would be a good opportunity to get some exercise.
The market has finally closed, marking a steady end to the year. I just finished lunch. How are things on your end? Any plans for New Year's Eve tonight?
Mom, I'm heading to the riverside to take photos of the New Year's Eve night view. I've brought warm clothes and hot water, so don't worry. You all stay warm at home too. Happy New Year!

Haoran, you did an excellent job in today's sharing session, especially in presenting the arguments on technological self-reliance and consumption recovery with clear logic. Regarding the supplementary data report you mentioned after the meeting, could you please send me a copy when convenient? Thank you! — Sun Xiaoya
summarized_info: Feng Haoran received a text message from his colleague Sun Xiaoya, which directly mentioned the terms "technological self-reliance and innovation" and "consumption recovery," and praised the content of the sharing session.

message_content: Yunfei: Haoran, regarding the financing project we discussed during our run today, the pressure is greater than expected, but the team is making progress. How are the preparations for your meeting this afternoon?
Luo Zhenyu: Haoran, here's a link for the Soviet stamp series we discussed yesterday. Don't forget to check the UN series as well—I often use that website.
Gao Yunfei: The investment directions discussed during today's run were quite enlightening, and the technology sector is worth exploring in greater depth.
Mom: Was the contract signing smooth? Has the down payment been settled? Remember to share the news with your dad.

Mr. Lu, thank you for your time this afternoon. Regarding the plan we discussed for selling the apartment, I will prepare the documents as soon as possible. As for the listing price and the arrangements for viewings, I will await your further instructions.
Zheng Wenbo: I've already arrived at the Lanzhou Lamian restaurant, on Jinying Road. Please come quickly.
Yesterday, I checked the basil on the balcony, and it is growing very well with lush new leaves.
Feng Haoran: On the way to the office, I was thinking about the presentation with Huang Siqi this afternoon and felt that the logic still needed to be refined.

Lao Luo, I had a very rewarding visit to the Stamp Museum today! The special exhibition "Space Epic on a Small Square" was fantastic—I took a lot of photos. I also bought the aerospace commemorative envelope you mentioned at the store and got a set for you as well.
Feng Haoran: I'm almost at the art gallery. Let's meet at the sculpture by the entrance! I heard the exhibits today are quite impressive.
Feng Haoran, the materials have been received and preparations are complete. I am available this Thursday afternoon for a detailed discussion.
Mr. Qian, confirming the performance review interview scheduled for Thursday afternoon at 3 PM. I will attend punctually.
Haoran, I tried to reach you earlier but couldn't get through. Were you focused on studying? I'd like to ask for your advice regarding CFA exam preparation materials.
Zhang Mingxuan: Haoran, have you been in touch with Ayuan recently? It seems like something's going on with him.
Feng Haoran: We had a video call last week. What's wrong? Did something happen to him?
Zhang Mingxuan: I just heard this from another friend in Shenzhen. Their company recently had a major layoff, and A Yuan unfortunately was on the list.
Feng Haoran: No wonder he seemed down during our last chat, only mentioning a change in his job without going into details. Now with his income cut off, the pressure must be significant.

Zhang Mingxuan: Yes, he said he wants to take a break first and carefully consider whether to continue working for others or try taking on projects independently. We can have a thorough chat with him when we return to Wuhan for the Chinese New Year.
Peng Yuqing: What new songs have you been listening to lately? Share some playlists with me to listen to while running.
Feng Haoran: I haven't been listening to much new music lately. Instead, I've been replaying Mao Buyi's "A Guide for Young Birds" countless times.
Peng Yuqing: Huh? I remember you used to prefer music with strong beats or purely instrumental pieces. How come you've suddenly become a fan of Mao Buyi?

Feng Haoran: Tastes can change. The songs in this album, like "So I Didn't Wash My Hair" and "Diary at Sea," have lyrics that are written with such authenticity—capturing the mundane details and warmth of ordinary life—that they really help you settle down. Listening to them while running even brings a unique sense of healing.
Peng Yuqing: Understood. After such intense mental exertion, Consultant Feng needs some "earthly human warmth" to restore balance. I'll give it a listen later as well.
Peng Yuqing: Haoran, have you heard any news about Dong Haoran recently? It feels like he hasn't been active in the group chat for a long time.
Feng Haoran: I just had a video call with him last week. He’s been busy with a major project recently and hasn’t had much time for casual chats.
Peng Yuqing: What major event? Is he getting promoted again?

Feng Haoran: It wasn't work. He had been eyeing a foreclosed property in Nanshan, Shenzhen for almost half a year, and he finally managed to win the bid for it last week. The process was quite nerve-wracking, with intense bidding in the final few rounds.
Peng Yuqing: Wow! Congratulations to him! He's really put down roots in Shenzhen now. We'll have to get him to treat us to a meal sometime.
Luo Zhenyu: Xiao Feng, the stamp market has been a bit sluggish lately. Have you made any new acquisitions on your end?

Feng Haoran: Brother Luo, my interests have shifted a bit recently. While I used to collect many landscape, flower, and bird paintings, I'm now more focused on themes that reflect the development of the era and the aesthetics of engineering.
Luo Zhenyu: Oh? Which specific area? Aerospace? Transportation?

Feng Haoran: Yes, bridges in transportation infrastructure. I believe modern bridges, especially those cross-sea bridges and canyon bridges built in China in recent years, are themselves a combination of technology and art, making them particularly valuable for collection. I am systematically collecting all "Modern Bridge Construction" thematic stamps issued since the founding of the People's Republic of China, ranging from the Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge to the Hong Kong-Zhuhai-Macao Bridge.
Luo Zhenyu: This is a great topic! It not only traces the historical context but also bears the imprint of national development. I'll keep an eye out for early bridge tickets for you.
Zheng Wenbo: Haoran, shall we meet at the usual spot at noon? I noticed a new Hunan restaurant opened downstairs in our company building today. They say the chopped chili fish head is pretty good.
Feng Haoran: Sounds good, I'm actually a bit hungry. Shall we meet in the lobby downstairs at 12:20?
Zheng Wenbo: Okay. By the way, I just chatted with one of my childhood friends for a while, and he's been quite troubled lately.
Feng Haoran: Oh? What's the matter, something work-related?

Zheng Wenbo: Well, he has been engaged in architectural design for nearly ten years. Recently, he mentioned feeling particularly burnt out, as the projects have become monotonous and lack a sense of achievement. He is struggling with whether to completely change careers but is worried that starting over would be too difficult. He feels stuck in an awkward position and is quite uncertain about the future.

Luo Zhenyu: Haoran, the stamp market has been experiencing some fluctuations recently. Have you been following the 'World Famous Paintings' series? A few sets have seen price corrections, which feels like an opportunity.
Feng Haoran: Old Luo, I've seen it. But to be honest, my recent collecting interests have shifted somewhat.
Luo Zhenyu: Oh? What has it shifted to? I remember you used to be quite interested in both artistic and landscape photography.

Feng Haoran: Well, now I'm more inclined to systematically collect stamps that document our country's hardcore technological advancements. For instance, aerospace engineering, lunar exploration, deep-sea exploration, and so on. I feel they hold both collectible value and epochal significance. It's quite awe-inspiring to see images of rocket launches and submersibles diving printed within such a small space.

Luo Zhenyu: This is a promising direction! The theme of building a strong nation through science and technology is well-conceived, and the issuance of such commemorative stamps is relatively well-controlled. In the long run, it shows great potential. I'll keep an eye out for you.

Zhang Mingxuan: Haoran, I just finished a meeting with my colleagues, and I'm exhausted. The product manager in our team, the one I mentioned to you last time who works extremely hard, has had a recurrence of his cervical spondylosis.
Feng Haoran: That serious? Last time you mentioned he often works overtime until very late.

Zhang Mingxuan: Yes, this time it's quite serious. The doctor said I need to be hospitalized for a week of physical therapy. The project schedule will be affected again. But don't worry, it has nothing to do with your side of the business.
Feng Haoran: Health is the foundation of success. You should also take care and not follow his example. Our profession involves prolonged sitting, so I've recently started practicing yoga.
Peng Yuqing: Are you free this weekend? I found a newly opened dessert shop. It's said their tiramisu is absolutely amazing.
Feng Haoran: Sure. However, I'm not particularly interested in sweets these days. Instead, I've become quite fond of coffee with a pronounced sourness.
Peng Yuqing: Huh? Didn't you used to prefer drinks that were more bitter?

Feng Haoran: My taste has changed. Recently, I've been particularly fond of lightly roasted Ethiopian Yirgacheffe, with its bright citrus and jasmine notes and a moderate acidity—very refreshing. Boss Shen just got a new batch in, and I stocked up quite a bit.

Peng Yuqing: Got it. Master Feng is going for the refined route now. Then bring some of your prized beans this weekend, and we'll go to a dessert shop. You can have pour-over coffee, and I'll have cake.
Huang Siqi: Mr. Feng, tomorrow's video conference is scheduled in Independent Meeting Room No. 3. Please prepare the relevant materials.
Peng Yuqing: The dinner address is set at Xihu Jianxin Resettlement Community. See you at 7 p.m.
Zhang Mingxuan: Haoran, have you been in touch with Ayuan recently? He seems a bit down lately.
Feng Haoran: We had a video chat last week. What's going on with him? Is it still about work-related matters?

Zhang Mingxuan: Yes, his AI large model project has been in development for nearly a year. As a result, the core algorithmic approach of their team was preempted by a team at ByteDance, which published a paper on it and even open-sourced part of the code.
Feng Haoran: This is indeed a significant blow. It essentially nullifies the uniqueness of our early investments and the first-mover advantage.

Zhang Mingxuan: Indeed, A-Yuan mentioned that the atmosphere in their team is quite low at the moment. They are unsure about the next steps for the project—whether to continue delving deeper or to adjust the direction. It seems he is quite confused.
Shen Xinyi: Consultant Feng, we recently received a new batch of Ethiopian Yirgacheffe G1, washed process, with a very clean flavor. Would you like to try it?
Feng Haoran: Great, come over in the afternoon. By the way, Boss Shen, I've recently settled on my brewing parameters and feel like I've found a relatively universal sweet spot range.
Shen Xinyi: Oh? Do tell. You were always making adjustments before.

Feng Haoran: I now consistently use a water temperature of 92 degrees Celsius, with a coffee-to-water ratio of 1:16, and employ the four-six method for brewing. The total brewing time is controlled to around three minutes. This approach yields a fuller body with a balanced acidity and sweetness, making it suitable for most medium-light roasted beans.
Shen Xinyi: A very classic parameter combination with high stability. I'll use your parameters to brew a pot of the newly arrived Yirgacheffe this afternoon and see how it performs.
Peng Yuqing: Haoran, it's been a while since we last talked. Have you been busy lately?
Feng Haoran: Not bad, just finished a project. How about you, anything new lately?
Peng Yuqing: I was scrolling through my WeChat Moments yesterday and saw a post from our university classmate Zhou Yuwei. It seems she has some big happy news.
Feng Haoran: Oh? What happened to Weiwei? I remember she's been doing analysis at HSBC and is quite impressive.

Peng Yuqing: Exactly, she just posted her transcript and certificate online. She finally passed the CFA Level III exam! It's really not easy, studying while working. Should we congratulate her in the group chat?

Gao Yunfei: Haoran, what a refreshing run today. By the way, I noticed the street photography photos you've been posting on your social media feed recently have much better texture than before. Did you get new equipment?
Feng Haoran: Haha, you've got me. I didn't replace all the equipment; the main changes were in the shooting approach and the lenses I typically use.
Gao Yunfei: Oh? How so? I remember you used to prefer that 24-70mm zoom lens, saying it was convenient.

Feng Haoran: Yes, but now I feel that while zoom lenses are convenient, they fall a bit short in terms of image quality and atmosphere. For the past few months, when I go out for street photography, I've basically been using just a 50mm f/1.4 prime lens.

Feng Haoran: The shallow depth of field created by a large aperture and that unique bokeh effect are particularly suitable for capturing the fleeting emotions and interplay of light and shadow of street subjects. It is currently my most preferred style.

Manager Feng, I will join the meeting on time this afternoon. Regarding the latest updates on our investment portfolio, especially the impact of changes in the external environment, I hope we can focus on discussing these points during today's meeting.
Peng Yuqing: Haoran, have you heard? Wenjing has good news!
Feng Haoran: I haven't heard about it. What good news? Isn't she working as a financial manager at China Merchants Bank?
Peng Yuqing: That's right! Her bank's Shanghai branch is holding an internal competition for positions, and she has applied for a role in the private banking department.
Feng Haoran: How did it turn out? She is very capable, so she should have a good chance.
Peng Yuqing: The results just came out, and she succeeded! She is now the deputy manager of the Private Banking Department. We should find a time to congratulate her.
Gao Yunfei: Haoran, I noticed the style of the photos you've been posting on your Moments seems to have changed a bit recently?
Feng Haoran: That's quite observant of you. I have indeed been exploring a new direction recently, and I find it quite interesting.
Gao Yunfei: In what direction? Still street photography?
Feng Haoran: Yes, still street photography, but more focused. I've recently been particularly fond of capturing those forgotten corners in the old city districts.

Feng Haoran: For instance, the mottled walls, rusted iron gates, and the textures of vintage shop signs. These details carry a sense of narrative steeped in time, embodying a different kind of beauty compared to the sleekness of modern architecture.
Peng Yuqing: Haoran, have you been in touch with Wenjing recently? She seems to be experiencing some career anxiety.
Feng Haoran: We had a video chat last week. She has been at China Merchants Bank for several years and feels she has hit a bottleneck in her career development.

Peng Yuqing: Yes, she mentioned that a headhunter is trying to recruit her for a newly established private equity fund company, where she would be responsible for product design. The compensation and career development prospects sound promising, but she is also concerned about the risks.

Feng Haoran: Well, the platform stability varies greatly from a major bank to a startup private equity firm. I analyzed the pros and cons with her and let her weigh them herself. After all, in Shanghai, there are many opportunities, but the cost of trial and error is also high.
Gao Yunfei: Haoran, I noticed the recent photos of the Xiangjiang River nightscape you posted on your Moments. The color tones feel different from before—they have more character.
Feng Haoran: Haha, you're quite observant. I've been experimenting with a new post-processing approach recently, aiming to reduce the dominance of colors.
Gao Yunfei: What exactly is the approach? The overall image feels a bit dark, but the details that should be bright are very clear. It seems like the contrast hasn't been pushed too high.

Feng Haoran: Exactly, that's the feeling you described. Recently, I've been favoring a cinematic-style color grading—overall darkening, reducing contrast, and lowering color saturation. The focus isn't on highlighting a specific object but on creating the atmosphere and narrative of the entire scene.
Gao Yunfei: Understood. It's more about emotional expression rather than just being "good-looking." That's quite sophisticated.
I read a lengthy article on the plane about ETFs, and the analysis of the healthcare sector was quite in-depth.
Peng Yuqing: The stir-fried seasonal vegetables you ordered are served. Please try them.
Haoran: Mom, the test from the lab department is just done, and the ECG room is also finished. I'm going to pay the fees now.

Peng Yuqing: Haoran, I just searched and found that both Daweshan and Hupingshan we discussed last time seem quite suitable for a summer trip. Which one do you prefer? Shall we discuss it in detail next week?
summarized_info: Peng Yuqing sent a text message to Feng Haoran, mentioning the camping location options discussed last time and suggesting a follow-up detailed discussion.

message_content: I had a meal with Yuqing yesterday and talked for a while, which helped relieve a lot of stress. I discussed both work-related matters and family issues, and now I feel much more relaxed.
Zhang San: Haoran, is the NFC orange juice you just bought at the convenience store tasty? I also want to give it a try.
Brother Feng, the policy change points discussed during today's lunch were quite enlightening. I will send you a detailed analysis later.
Dong Haoran: Haozi, are you busy? Do you have a moment to talk?
Feng Haoran: Just got home, not busy. What's up, Haozi? You sound a bit off.
Dong Haoran: Sigh, I just feel really pent up. That new social product incubation project I've been leading for over half a year was officially suspended by upper management today.
Feng Haoran: What's going on? I remember you said last time that the progress was good and the team was highly motivated.

Dong Haoran: They said it's due to an overall strategic realignment of the company, with resources being concentrated on more core, profitable business lines. Our exploratory innovation project is among the first to be affected. It feels like six months of hard work has gone to waste, and the team is quite demoralized.
Gao Yunfei: Same time and place tomorrow? I heard you've been putting more effort into coffee lately.
Feng Haoran: No problem, see you at the foot of the mountain at 6:30. Yes, I've been trying beans from different regions and processing methods lately—it's quite interesting.
Gao Yunfei: Any new findings? I'm still the same, surviving on American coffee.

Feng Haoran: Having had my fill of traditional washed and sun-dried coffees, I’m now more captivated by anaerobic fermentation processing. Although it’s controversial, that explosive berry and wine-like aroma, along with the distinctive fermented notes, create such rich layers. Every brew feels like opening a blind box.
Gao Yunfei: Sounds complicated. I still can't appreciate it. Let's talk more during our run tomorrow. I need to go put the kid to sleep.
Dong Haoran: Haozi, have you been in touch with Liu Haoran lately? He's been making quite a stir over there.
Feng Haoran: We briefly discussed it last week, and he mentioned he's considering a new direction. I haven't asked for specifics yet. Have you heard anything?

Dong Haoran: He has just formally submitted his resignation and stepped down from his position as a product manager at Tencent. He said that after working for so many years at a major tech company, he wants to try something on his own.
Feng Haoran: Wow, that was quick. Have you decided what to do next? Or are you planning to rest first?

Dong Haoran: He said he plans to take one or two months off first to spend time with his family. After that, he intends to team up with two former colleagues from Tencent to start a company in Shenzhen, focusing on the implementation of AI application scenarios. The specific details are still being refined. It takes quite some courage.
Luo Zhenyu: Haoran, the stamp market has been warming up recently. Which sectors are you focusing on?
Feng Haoran: Hello, Brother Luo. I've recently narrowed my focus of interest a bit, mainly looking at stamps with the theme of aerospace technology.
Luo Zhenyu: This direction is promising, with a compelling narrative to tell. What specifically are you focusing on—the design or the distribution background?

Feng Haoran: There are two aspects. One is the technological connotations and era imprints carried by the stamps themselves, such as the Chang'e lunar exploration and the space station, which record our country's technological advancements and hold significant historical meaning.

Feng Haoran: Secondly, from the perspective of our industry, this type of theme aligns with national strategies and garners high public attention. In the long run, I believe its value as an alternative asset allocation and its potential for appreciation are worthy of in-depth study.
Zhang Mingxuan: Haoran, what have you been up to lately? I had a meal with Ayuan last weekend and heard something quite interesting from him.
Feng Haoran: Just finished the meeting. What's up with A Yuan? Is he tinkering with his code again or has he discovered some delicious food?
Zhang Mingxuan: Neither. It's his expensive hobby. He said he finally won the stamp he'd been talking about for years at an online stamp auction in Shenzhen recently.
Feng Haoran: Oh? Which one? I remember he mentioned before that he wanted a set of zodiac dragon head coins, or was it the aerospace series?

Zhang Mingxuan: It's a souvenir sheet issued for the 1997 Hong Kong handover, the kind with gold foil. He said the condition is particularly excellent, and although the price is quite high, he feels it holds special commemorative significance, fulfilling a long-held wish.

Shen Xinyi: Consultant Feng, we recently received a new batch of anaerobic sun-dried Catimor from Baoshan, Yunnan. It has a very distinctive flavor profile, with notes of red wine and tropical fruits. I've saved half a pound for you. Would you like to come and try it tomorrow?

Feng Haoran: Thank you for your concern, Mr. Shen. However, my taste seems to have become a bit "back to basics" lately. I tried quite a few special processing methods recently, but after the novelty wore off, I actually started feeling a bit of aesthetic fatigue.
Shen Xinyi: Oh? Could you elaborate? Are you considering changing the origin or the roast level?

Feng Haoran: Changes in brewing methods. Over the past few weeks, I've been brewing coffee at home and find myself gravitating more toward traditional washed beans, such as those from Guatemala or Kenya AA. I feel that the distinct acidity and clean taste better highlight the inherent flavors of the origin, making them less "overpowering."

Shen Xinyi: Understood. This is a return from pursuing "excitement" to "authentic flavor." I happen to have a newly arrived Colombian Huilan washed coffee here, medium-light roast, with distinct citrus and nutty notes, very clean. Would you like to try this one tomorrow?
Zhang Mingxuan: Haoran, how have you been lately? It must be getting hot in Changsha.
Feng Haoran: Yeah, it's time to start wearing short sleeves. How about in Shenzhen? What have you been busy with lately?
Zhang Mingxuan: Same as usual, projects keep piling up. By the way, do you still remember my friend Wang Lei I mentioned before? The one who works on AI algorithms.
Feng Haoran: It rings a bell. Is it that unicorn company in Nanshan?

Zhang Mingxuan: Yes, that's him! Just got the news that he was successfully promoted to Technical Director last month, responsible for the R&D of the entire AI product line. He's really impressive. A few of us friends are planning to celebrate for him this weekend.
Zheng Wenbo: Haoran, how about trying that newly opened Hunan restaurant downstairs at noon? I heard their chopped chili fish head is quite good.
Feng Haoran: Sure. By the way, I recently tried some new Ethiopian beans at Boss Shen's place.
Zheng Wenbo: Oh? What's so special about it? I still prefer dark roast coffee. It's strong enough.

Feng Haoran: My taste preferences have changed; I'm not as focused on richness and body these days. Lately, I've been particularly drawn to beans with bright, lively citrus acidity, like washed Sidamo or Yirgacheffe. They taste very refreshing and are perfect for summer.
Zheng Wenbo: Haha, you pour-over enthusiasts are so particular. Alright, see you at 12 o'clock in the lobby on the first floor.
Zhang Mingxuan: Haoran, how has the weather been in Changsha lately? It's been damp and cold here in Shenzhen.
Feng Haoran: It's okay. It's dry and cold, which is more bearable than the magic attack in Shenzhen. What have you been up to lately?

Zhang Mingxuan: Sigh, there are some family matters. My father just had knee replacement surgery last week and is currently recovering in the hospital. I need to go back to Wuhan this weekend to check on him.

Feng Haoran: Ah? Was Uncle Zhang's surgery successful? Joint issues really require more attention as one gets older. Please send him my regards and wish him a speedy recovery. Let me know if you need any help.

Zhang Mingxuan: Thanks, bro! The surgery went quite well, but the recovery period is relatively long. Are your parents in good health? Remind them to keep warm more often, and not to take it lightly like my dad used to.
Shen Xinyi: Mr. Feng, a new batch of beans has arrived today. There's a Panamanian Geisha washed coffee with an amazing flavor profile. Would you like me to reserve some for you?
Feng Haoran: Thank you for your consideration, Mr. Shen. I'll pass on the Geisha coffee for now, as my taste preferences have shifted a bit recently.
Shen Xinyi: Oh? What new discoveries have been made?

Feng Haoran: I used to always chase after those light roast beans with explosive floral and fruity acidity, like Ethiopian Yirgacheffe. Recently, perhaps due to the cold weather or the need for a more steady companion while preparing for the CFA exam, I've started to find medium-dark roast beans quite interesting.

Feng Haoran: For example, the Colombian Huilan coffee you recommended last time, with its medium-dark roast, offers a rich taste of nuts and dark chocolate upon the first sip, followed by a hint of caramel sweetness in the aftertaste. It felt particularly grounding when paired with reading and problem-solving at night. Could you recommend some beans with a similar style?

Shen Xinyi: Got it! Seems like we're shifting from "light and fresh" to "bold and intense," haha. I happen to have a Guatemalan bean, medium-dark roast, with a full body and notes of roasted almonds and milk chocolate. Shall I save a portion for you to try tomorrow?
Peng Yuqing: Haoran, are you busy? I just got off the phone with Wenjing, and she seemed a bit down.
Feng Haoran: Just finished the meeting. What's wrong with Wen Jing? Is she unhappy with her work?
Peng Yuqing: Well, she's recently been working on a rather complex family trust case, and the client has very high demands.

Peng Yuqing: She mentioned that during the risk isolation phase of the project design, she had a completely different opinion from a senior colleague in the team. The colleague, who has extensive experience, insisted on their own viewpoint, which put a lot of pressure on her.

Feng Haoran: Understood. Such professional disagreements are indeed tricky, especially when involving high-net-worth clients. I will also give her a call later to discuss and see if I can offer some advice regarding the trust structure.
Luo Zhenyu: Haoran, there's a batch of old commemorative and special stamps in good condition on the stamp market recently. Would you be interested in taking a look?
Feng Haoran: Hello, Brother Luo! Thank you for sharing. However, my collecting interests have shifted a bit recently, and I'm not as enthusiastic about new stamps as before.
Luo Zhenyu: Oh? Which direction has it shifted towards?

Feng Haoran: I feel that the narrative potential of a single stamp is somewhat limited. Nowadays, I am more fascinated by those covers with clear postmarks and genuine mailing traces, such as first-day covers. The time and location information they carry add a sense of history and uniqueness to the collection.

Luo Zhenyu: This shift shows good taste! Collecting postally used covers indeed has a higher threshold and offers more interest. I have a few domestic postally used covers from the 1950s and 1960s on hand, and I'll take photos to show you later.
Peng Yuqing: Haoran, have you heard? Wenjing recently had a change in her job.
Feng Haoran: Oh? Wasn't she working as a financial manager at the Shanghai Branch of China Merchants Bank? Where has she been transferred to?

Peng Yuqing: Yes, it's an internal transfer within China Merchants Bank Shanghai Branch. She has been transferred to the Private Banking Department, specifically serving clients with assets of ten million yuan or more. She said the challenges are significant, but the opportunities are also great.

Feng Haoran: That is indeed a great opportunity, as private banking has promising prospects. She is highly capable and should be able to adapt quickly. Next time she returns to Changsha, we must celebrate properly for her.
Luo Zhenyu: Haoran, there's a new batch of goods in the stamp market recently, including several exquisite sets from the Republic of China period. Would you be interested in taking a look?
Feng Haoran: Old Luo, thank you for sharing. However, my collecting focus has shifted a bit recently, and my interest in Republic of China stamps has temporarily waned.
Luo Zhenyu: Oh? So which area are you focusing on now? Is it zodiac stamps or space-themed ones?

Feng Haoran: Neither. It might be due to work pressure and my love for the outdoors, but I am currently particularly fascinated by natural scenery and wildlife stamps issued by countries around the world. Examples like Canada's polar bears, Norway's fjords, and Kenya's wildlife are incredibly relaxing to look at, and their composition and colors are especially impressive.
Luo Zhenyu: Haha, that hobby actually complements your love for camping photography quite well. I'll keep an eye out for you and let you know if I come across any good natural-themed foreign stamps.

Zhang Mingxuan: Haoran, technology stocks have been quite volatile in Shenzhen recently. How are the clients on your side feeling? One of our team members recently took paternity leave, so the workload has been distributed among the rest of us.
Feng Haoran: Xuanzi, the clients are fine, they've gotten used to the volatility. Who in your team is on paternity leave? I remember only Xiao Li and Xiao Wang in your team are married, right?

Zhang Mingxuan: It's Wang Lei, the one sitting diagonally across from me. He just had a baby last weekend—a daughter—and he's over the moon. With him on leave, we'll have to keep an eye on two projects for him.

Feng Haoran: Congratulations to him! The birth of a daughter is a significant event. You all have been working hard; when he returns, he should treat everyone to a meal. By the way, regarding the ETF you asked about last time, I think it would be wise to observe it for another week.
Peng Yuqing: Haoran, are you free this weekend? I found a newly opened Hunan restaurant, and it's said their chopped chili fish head is absolutely amazing.
Feng Haoran: Sure, Saturday noon? I've recently found some great coffee beans, I'll bring some for you to try.
Peng Yuqing: Great! Have your tastes changed again recently? I remember you used to always drink the kind with a strong bitter flavor.

Feng Haoran: There has been a bit of a change. I used to think the rich, robust flavor of dark roast was suitable for waking up in the morning, but now I prefer medium-light roasts instead. They have a bright acidity and more prominent floral and fruity notes, making me feel refreshed all day long. Boss Shen has brought in a few Ethiopian beans, and they are processed very cleanly.
Peng Yuqing: That sounds very professional! I'll definitely savor Master Feng's pour-over coffee carefully this Saturday. I'll send you the restaurant address.
Xinran, have you contacted the hotel planning team for Dad's birthday banquet? I've basically completed the draft budget here and am waiting for your update to finalize it.
Dong Haoran: Haozi, what have you been up to lately? I’ve got some good news and can’t wait to share it with you.
Feng Haoran: Just finished the debriefing meeting. What's the good news? You seem so excited—has there been a breakthrough in the project?
Dong Haoran: It's not about work, it's about collecting! Do you remember that "Golden Monkey" stamp I've been talking about all this time?
Feng Haoran: Of course I remember, the T46 Monkey Stamp, the hard currency in philately. So, have you made any progress?

Dong Haoran: More than just a clue! Last week, there was a small-scale boutique auction in Shenzhen, and I gritted my teeth and secured it! It's a block of four 1980 Monkey stamps in excellent condition. Although the price was steep, my dream has finally come true!

Shen Xinyi: Good afternoon, Consultant Feng. A new batch of Costa Rican beans has just arrived, including both sun-dried and washed varieties, along with a small amount of yellow honey-processed ones. Would you like to give them a try?

Feng Haoran: Mr. Shen, you're really well-informed. My taste has changed a bit recently. Sometimes the intensity of sun-dried coffee feels a bit heavy, and while washed coffee offers high clarity, it lacks some complexity.
Shen Xinyi: Oh? So it seems you've been exploring new flavor profiles recently?

Feng Haoran: Yes. Last month, I tried several honey-processed coffees, especially the yellow honey, and felt I had found a balance. They offer good sweetness and body, yet aren't as wild as natural-processed coffees, with bright and clean acidity.

Shen Xinyi: Got it! Then I'll save a pack of Costa Rican beans with yellow honey processing for you. You can pick it up after work? This one has a honey-like sweetness with a black tea finish in the aftertaste, which should suit your current taste preferences.
Dong Haoran: Haozi, have you been in touch with Liu Haoran recently? It seems things aren't going well on his end.
Feng Haoran: We briefly chatted last week, and he mentioned the company's organizational restructuring. What's going on? Have you heard any news?

Dong Haoran: He had a video call with me yesterday and seemed quite down. The social e-commerce project his team was responsible for was completely scrapped by headquarters because it failed to meet the ROI target.
Feng Haoran: The project is gone, what about the team?

Dong Haoran: The team is highly likely to be disbanded and reorganized. As a product manager, he is currently looking for internal transfer opportunities through the "Internal Mobility Program," but there are very few suitable positions available. HR has already hinted that if he cannot find a receiving department by the end of the month, he may have to go through the optimization process. It truly is a case of misfortunes never coming singly.
Luo Zhenyu: Haoran, there have been some fluctuations in the stamp market recently. Have you been following it? Have you acquired any new stamps?

Feng Haoran: Brother Luo, I have indeed been looking into it recently. However, my interests have shifted a bit—I no longer chase after popular zodiac themes or commemorative stamps for major events like I used to.
Luo Zhenyu: Oh? Which field has it shifted to? Is it more inclined towards traditional culture, or modern design?

Feng Haoran: It's a relatively niche but personally fascinating area. I recently became captivated by the Arctic and Antarctic through a documentary, which led me to start collecting stamps from various countries featuring themes such as polar expeditions, research stations, auroras, and polar animals.

Luo Zhenyu: This topic is interesting! Countries like Finland, Norway, Canada, and Argentina have produced many high-quality stamps. I think I have an early Canadian polar bear stamp—I’ll look for it and show you later.
Zhang Mingxuan: Haoran, have you been in touch with Ayuan recently? He seems to be having some career-related concerns.
Feng Haoran: Not yet, I've been busy with my performance review lately. What's wrong with him? Is he still having a hard time at Tencent?
Zhang Mingxuan: It's not that he's unhappy. It's that a startup offered him a very attractive compensation package to poach him, which is considerably higher than what he's currently earning.
Feng Haoran: That's great. Is he interested?

Zhang Mingxuan: He is tempted, but he's deeply conflicted. After all, Tencent is a major platform and offers stability. Although that startup has promising prospects, what if it fails? He talked with me for a long time but still couldn't make up his mind.
Gao Yunfei: Haoran, same time and place for running tomorrow? I heard you've recently found some good coffee beans again?
Feng Haoran: No problem. The beans were purchased from Boss Shen. She recently brought in a new batch, and the quality is quite good.
Gao Yunfei: Do you have any current preferences when selecting coffee beans? I'm completely clueless about it, but I notice you drink it often.

Feng Haoran: It depends on my mood and the time of day. In the morning, I prefer something rich and balanced, like Colombian Huila coffee, with its nutty and chocolate notes—it’s refreshing without being too acidic. In the afternoon or evening, I might go for something bright and fruity, like Yirgacheffe.
Gao Yunfei: Understood. The "sense of balance" you had this morning is the key. I'll keep that in mind when I order at the café next time.

Zhang Mingxuan: Haoran, the technology industry in Shenzhen has been quite volatile recently. I have a colleague I'm on good terms with, who works in hardware R&D. Their department is currently restructuring its business lines, and he might be laid off. He's really worried about it.
Feng Haoran: Xuanzi, this is indeed a hurdle. Hardware R&D experience is actually quite valuable, but the current macro environment isn't very favorable for certain niche sectors. What are his plans?

Zhang Mingxuan: He is also looking for opportunities, but his mindset is a bit shaken. He was doing fine originally, but suddenly they said the business would shrink, and the entire team might be laid off. I advised him not to rush for now, to update his resume properly, and I also offered to help him inquire if there are any headcounts available in other departments at our company.

Feng Haoran: Well, maintaining a steady mindset is key. If he needs advice on career planning or resume writing, he can add me on WeChat to chat. Although different industries can feel worlds apart, some general job-seeking principles are universally applicable.

Shen Xinyi: Mr. Feng, we recently received a batch of new beans. There's a Colombian anaerobic fermentation coffee with a very distinctive flavor profile, featuring notes of wine and berries. Would you like to give it a try?
Feng Haoran: Mr. Shen, that sounds promising. I've recently been quite fascinated by beans processed with anaerobic fermentation. The complex and somewhat wild layers of flavor are truly captivating.

Shen Xinyi: Haha, you know your stuff. For this coffee bean brewed as a pour-over, I think pairing it with some bittersweet dark chocolate is the best—they complement each other without overpowering the flavors.

Feng Haoran: Great minds think alike. Last weekend, I brewed an anaerobic coffee at home and paired it with a 70% dark chocolate. The rich flavors blended perfectly, much more enjoyable than pairing it with overly sweet pastries. I’ll come by tomorrow afternoon to try yours.
Tomorrow at the usual spot, the east gate of Yuelu Mountain, 6:40. Don't be late.
Wu Junjie: Haoran, have you been in touch with any of our university classmates recently? I had a phone call with Zhou Yuwei last week.
Feng Haoran: Ajie, I've been busy lately and haven't been in touch much. How is Yuwei doing in Shanghai?
Wu Junjie: There's a bit of a headache at work. She is currently working on a cross-border green bond project, which seems to involve helping a Chinese enterprise issue bonds in Europe.

Wu Junjie: She said the biggest challenge is the misalignment between the ESG rating standards on both sides. Europe has a very complex system, which differs from the standards recognized by domestic regulatory authorities. The back-and-forth communication and revisions have significantly slowed down the project progress.
Feng Haoran: This is indeed a pain point in current cross-border green finance. The integration of standards requires time. However, with Yuwei's capabilities, she should be able to handle it well.
Shen Xinyi: Mr. Feng, we've recently acquired a few excellent samples of Japanese whisky. Would you be interested in trying them? I know you have an interest in spirits as well as coffee.
Feng Haoran: You're well-informed, Mr. Shen. I have indeed been looking at some Japanese whiskies recently, but I haven't decided which one to purchase yet.
Shen Xinyi: So what do you mainly look for when selecting wine? The vintage? Or do you prefer the story behind a specific winery?
Feng Haoran: For me, both the vintage and the story serve as references. What I truly care about is the duration and evolution of the flavor in the mouth after taking a sip.

Feng Haoran: A good Japanese whisky should have a long finish, with the ability to gradually transition from the initial fruitiness and woody notes to more delicate spices or mineral undertones. This sense of complexity is more interesting than simply focusing on the intensity of smokiness or the age statement.
Shen Xinyi: Understood, aftertaste and complexity are your key criteria. Then I recommend you try this "Yoichi" - its finish is exceptional. Would you like to come over this weekend?
Dong Haoran: Haozi, are you free tonight? I'd like to have a video chat with you. I've been having some troubles at work recently.
Feng Haoran: Yes, I'm free. How about nine o'clock? What's the matter? Is the project not going smoothly?
Dong Haoran: Well, the data for the newly launched "Interest Circles" feature of the social product I'm responsible for is quite disappointing.

Dong Haoran: The user retention rate is far below expectations. The team is currently in heated debates over whether to continue optimizing this feature or to scrap it entirely and pursue a new direction. It's exhausting.
Feng Haoran: Understood. I'll help you analyze it via video call tonight. Don't worry too much for now—there's always a solution to data issues.
Zheng Wenbo: Haoran, want to grab coffee during lunch break? I found a new café behind our company, and they say the beans are pretty good.
Feng Haoran: Sure. But recently, Boss Shen recommended a sun-dried Ethiopian coffee bean to me, and I've become quite addicted to it at her shop.
Zheng Wenbo: Oh? What kind of flavor is it that makes you recommend it so highly?

Feng Haoran: It's quite special. The high-temperature segment features a very gentle, understated floral note, reminiscent of jasmine. As the temperature drops, the finish reveals a distinct green tea sensation, which is very refreshing and not at all cloying. It's perfect for an afternoon pick-me-up.
Zheng Wenbo: You've really piqued my interest. Shall we go try that at Boss Shen's place today?
Dong Haoran: Haozi, I just got off the phone with Xuanzi, and he's in much better spirits now.

Feng Haoran: That's good to hear. He really pushed himself too hard this time. To meet the launch deadline for Tencent's new project, he pulled all-nighters for a whole week and ended up in the hospital.

Dong Haoran: Yes, it was acute gastroenteritis. The pain was so severe that I couldn't straighten up, and my colleague had to take me to the emergency room. Fortunately, I was only hospitalized for three days, and now I'm recuperating at home.
Feng Haoran: We old classmates in Shenzhen should find time to visit him more often. Health is the foundation of all endeavors.

Luo Zhenyu: Haoran, several new stamp sets have recently been released in the stamp market, including a space exploration series and a newly designed set based on *Journey to the West*. Have you been following them?
Feng Haoran: Brother Luo, I've seen it. The design of that "Journey to the West" set is really good, with very dynamic visuals. My taste in collecting stamps has changed a bit recently.
Luo Zhenyu: Oh? Do tell, what type is preferred now?

Feng Haoran: I lean more towards those with cultural depth and narrative. For instance, I really liked the previously released series such as "Dream of the Red Chamber" and "Water Margin." They give a sense of showcasing a vast literary world within a limited space, which makes them more interesting to collect than mere scenic or achievement commemorative stamps.

Luo Zhenyu: I see, so you're following the "literati collection" approach. The classical literature masterpieces series is indeed classic and has high market recognition. I have a set of the old stamps for "Romance of the Three Kingdoms" in good condition; I'll show them to you next time.
Dong Haoran: Haoran, I just got off the phone with Xuanzi, and he's really overwhelmed lately.
Feng Haoran: What's wrong? He just settled down in Shenzhen, so he should be quite happy.

Dong Haoran: What's there to be happy about? I did buy a new apartment, but the renovation has been a huge pitfall. Before signing the contract, they made all sorts of grand promises, but now, right after the plumbing and electrical work was completed, they started adding extra charges for everything, and the construction timeline keeps getting delayed.

Feng Haoran: Sigh, these kinds of things are the most annoying. Xuanzi has a quick temper, so he's probably even more upset. I'll give him a call later to see if we can find a solution through the contract or the Consumer Association.
Dong Haoran: Alright, you have more experience, so help him vet this properly. He really got taken advantage of by that company called 'Meiju Decoration' this time.
Luo Zhenyu: Haoran, I recently saw a very nice set of T46 Monkey stamps in the stamp market, in excellent condition. Would you like to take a look at the pictures?
Feng Haoran: Thank you, Lao Luo. However, my collecting interests have shifted a bit recently, and I'm not as enthusiastic about new stamps anymore.
Luo Zhenyu: Oh? In which direction has it turned?

Feng Haoran: I've started to become fascinated with used stamps. I mean those old stamps that have been postmarked and genuinely circulated. I feel the time and stories they carry have more flavor than simply brand-new printed items. Recently, I've collected several covers from the 1980s that were sent from Wuhan to various places across the country. Studying the postal routes and postmarks on them is particularly interesting.
Luo Zhenyu: Haha, I understand! From pursuing 'appearance' to pursuing 'history,' you've really elevated your game. I also have some good resources for used stamps; I'll share them with you later.
